q1.question:
(TIEBREAKER EXAMPLE QUESTION) This denomination was wracked by the Landmarkism controversy in the 1850s, shortly after it
was founded under the leadership of William Bullein Johnson. This denomination split off over
the refusal of the Home Mission Society to appoint slaveholders as missionaries. For 10 points,
name this largest Protestant denomination in the United States.

(TIEBREAKER EXAMPLE QUESTION) The admirals who worked for this man included Gil Eanes (ee-AH-nesh) and Antonio Noli.
His capture of Ceuta (say-OO-tuh) and leadership of the Order of Christ gave him vast
disposable funds, which he used to create the first map that extended to Cape Bojador (boh-hahDOR). For 10 points, name this member of the Aviz Dynasty who never ascended to the
Portuguese throne but left his mark as a patron of expeditions at the start of the Age of
Exploration.

(30 pts) (TIEBREAKER EXAMPLE QUESTION) The loophole that nothing with "socially redeeming value" could meet the definition of
this thing led to the former spectacle of brief Shakespeare performances in incongruous
films. Attempts to define this thing led to the Supreme Court cases of Roth v. U.S. and (20 pts)
Miller v. California. This genre was the subject of Potter Stewart's quote "I (10 pts)

know it when
I see it." For 10 points, name this genre which slowly acquired First Amendment protections
despite its explicit content.

(30 pts) (TIEBREAKER EXAMPLE QUESTION) At the end of this war, the Penghu (pr. PEN-goo) Islands changed hands, as did the
Liaodong (luh-OW-dong) Peninsula. (20 pts)

The Port Arthur Massacre occurred during this
war, which ended with the transfer of the Pescadores (PESS-cuh-doorz) and Taiwan. (10 pts)

For 10 points, name this war ended by the Treaty of Shimonoseki (shim-OH-noh-SEK-ee)
between two Asian powers in 1895.
